{"parse":{"title":"Pishtacos","pageid":25150808,"revid":832345223,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about a suspected hoax of a Peruvian gang trafficking in human fat. For the South American mythological figure, see <a href=\"/wiki/Pishtaco\" title=\"Pishtaco\">Pishtaco</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Pishtacos</b> is a term <a href=\"/wiki/National_Police_of_Peru\" title=\"National Police of Peru\">Peruvian police</a> has used to refer to alleged Peruvian <a href=\"/wiki/Gangsters\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gangsters\">gangsters</a> who were suspected of murdering up to 60 people for <a href=\"/wiki/Human_fat\" title=\"Human fat\">their fat</a>, and sold it to intermediaries in <a href=\"/wiki/Lima\" title=\"Lima\">Lima</a>, who are thought to have then sold the <a href=\"/wiki/Adipose_tissue\" title=\"Adipose tissue\">fat</a> to laboratories in <a href=\"/wiki/Europe\" title=\"Europe\">Europe</a> for suspected use in <a href=\"/wiki/Cosmetics\" title=\"Cosmetics\">cosmetics</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Later, General Felix Murga, chief of police forces in Peru, had to take leave from his job when Peruvian ministries reported that the whole story was a hoax.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The hoax was apparently passed on to prevent further investigations on <a href=\"/wiki/Extrajudicial_killing\" title=\"Extrajudicial killing\">extrajudicial killings</a> by police forces.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Details_of_the_hoax\">Details of the hoax</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pishtacos&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Details of the hoax\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>According to the police, the first suspected gang member, Serapio Marcos, was arrested on November 3, 2009. Three others, Elmer Segundo Castillejos Aguero, Enedina Estela Claudio and ring leader Hilario Cudena Simon, were arrested on November 20. The gang was given the name for the mythological figure, the <a href=\"/wiki/Pishtaco\" title=\"Pishtaco\">Pishtaco</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Guardian_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Guardian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The police claimed that the suspects told them that they sold the fat at a price of $15,000 per liter, but medical experts cast doubt on that, saying that so much body fat is extracted in routine medical procedures such as <a href=\"/wiki/Liposuction\" title=\"Liposuction\">liposuction</a>, that there should not be such a high demand for it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The story was that the gang members severed victims' heads, arms and legs, removed organs and suspend torsos from hooks above <a href=\"/wiki/Candles\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Candles\">candles</a>, which warmed the flesh as the fat dripped into tubs below.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Guardian_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Guardian-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Peruvian police also claimed that they were searching for six additional members of the gang.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pishtacos&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"r